Option — encoding that a value might be missing.

Option of a is a sealed algebraic data type with exactly two cases. Some, carrying a value, means a value is present. None means there is no value.

It is the Scala replacement for null, and the difference is about honesty in the types. Null lies — a string that is sometimes null still claims to be a string at all times, and you discover the truth only at runtime, through a null pointer exception. An option of string tells the truth in the type itself — every caller is forced to acknowledge the possibility that the value is missing, because the type says so.

The standard library returns an option from any method that might legitimately have no answer — getting a key from a map, taking the head of a possibly-empty list, parsing a string to an integer. Most java application programming interfaces, by contrast, return null, so the idiom at the boundary is to wrap a java call in an option, which turns a possible null into a none. Picture asking a map for a key that is present and getting some of the value, asking for an absent key and getting none, and wrapping a possibly-null value so that null safely becomes none. From that boundary inward, your Scala code never has to fear a surprise null again.
